{"title_page": "Pat Williams (American football)", "text_new": "{{short description|American football player}}\n{{other people|Patrick Williams|Patrick Williams}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Pat Williams\n|image=Pat Williams at 2009 Pro Bowl.jpg\n|image_size=150\n|caption=Pat Williams in the [[2009 Pro Bowl]].\n|number=94\n|position=[[Defensive tackle]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1972|10|24|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Monroe, Louisiana]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=3\n|weight_lbs=317\n|highlights=\n* 3\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2007 Pro Bowl|2006]]\u2013[[2009 Pro Bowl|2008]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2007 All-Pro Team|2007]])\n|high_school=[[Wossman High School|Monroe (LA) Wossman]]\n|college=[[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]]\n|undraftedyear=1997\n|pastteams=\n* [[Buffalo Bills]] ({{NFL Year|1997}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2004}})\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|2005}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2010}})\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Tackle]]s\n|statvalue1=566\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack|Sack]]s\n|statvalue2=20.5\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue3=8\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue4=9\n|statlabel5=[[Interception]]s\n|statvalue5=1\n|statlabel6=[[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]]\n|statvalue6=2\n|nfl=WIL462033\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Williams Sr.''' (born October 24, 1972) is a former [[American football]] [[defensive tackle]] who played in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for fourteen seasons.  He played [[college football]] for [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M University]].  He was signed by the [[Buffalo Bills]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 1997.  Williams also played for the [[Minnesota Vikings]], with whom he was a three-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection. Marneshia Williams daughter Montrel Williams son\n\n==College career==\nAfter graduating from [[Wossman High School]] in Monroe, Louisiana, Williams attended [[Navarro College]], where he was a two-time [[junior college]] All-American in 1992 and 1993. He initially transferred to [[Texas A&M University]] in 1994, but failed the math portion of a junior-college exit exam and was ruled ineligible for the [[1994 NCAA Division I-A football season|1994 season]]. He transferred again to [[Northeastern Oklahoma A&M College]], where he graduated in 1995, before returning to Texas A&M. Williams earned 2nd-team All-SWC as a junior in 1995 in only 6 starts. He also started 8 games and appeared in 11 as a senior.\n\n==Professional career==\n===Buffalo Bills===\nWilliams went undrafted in the [[1997 NFL Draft]], and signed with the [[Buffalo Bills]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] the same year. He played in just one game his rookie season. During the 1998\u20132000 seasons, he was a regular contributor, but did not become a regular starter until the 2001 season. In 2000, he was named to USA Today\u2019s All-Joe Team, recognizing the NFL\u2019s most \"overlooked, ignored and hard-working\" players.<ref name=\"Minnesota Vikings Bio\" /> Williams intercepted his first career pass and returned it 20 yards for a touchdown, picking off [[Miami Dolphins]] quarterback [[A. J. Feeley]] on December 5, 2004, sealing the win for Buffalo 42-32 and breaking open a 3-point game with 1:55 left to play.<ref name=\"Minnesota Vikings Bio\" /> Williams was named 2003 winner of the [[Ed Block Courage Award]] by his teammates.<ref name=\"Minnesota Vikings Bio\">[http://www.vikings.com/team/roster/Pat-Williams/c7acea89-76de-4fda-98ae-2bd156bd8ce4 Minnesota Vikings Bio]</ref> During his final four seasons with the Bills (2001\u20132004), he started in all but four games. He became a free agent after the 2004 season.\n\n===Minnesota Vikings===\nPrior to the 2005 season, Williams signed with the [[Minnesota Vikings]], the 1st signing for the team in 2005 free agency and a priority signing. Following an advice by then defensive coordinator [[Mike Tomlin]], Williams lost 15 pounds in the offseason. Williams played [[nose tackle]] in the [[Minnesota Vikings]] [[4-3 defense]], with teammate [[Kevin Williams (defensive tackle)|Kevin Williams]] playing the Under Tackle position. They were known collectively as the \"Williams Wall\" as well as the \"Williams Wrecking Crew\" due to their physical presence at the line of scrimmage, an attribute that helped them lead the Vikings to the best rushing defense in the league for three consecutive seasons (2006-2008). As a player for the Vikings, he was selected to his first [[Pro Bowl]] in 2006, and followed with consecutive selections in 2007 and 2008. He was also a second-team All-Pro selection in 2007.\n\nOn December 2, 2008, Pat and teammate [[Kevin Williams (defensive tackle)|Kevin Williams]] were suspended for 4 games by the league for violating its anti-doping policy, for use of a [[diuretic]], which can be used a [[masking agent]] for [[steroid]] use.<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=NFL Suspends Six Players for Doping Violations |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/football/nfl/12/02/nfl.ap/index.html |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |publisher= |date=2008-12-02 |accessdate= |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205093105/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/football/nfl/12/02/nfl.ap/index.html |archivedate=December 5, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80cfe423&template=without-video&confirm=true|title=NFL suspends six players for four games each}}</ref> It is believed that the diuretic was found in a weight-loss supplement that he had been taking.<ref name=\"SI\" /> Williams, along with Kevin Williams, appealed the suspension to a Minnesota federal court; the judge ruled against the NFL's decision and allowed all suspended players, including Williams, to play until a further review of the case.\n\nOn April 28, 2011, the [[Minnesota Supreme Court]] declined to consider Williams' appeal of the case, clearing the way for the [[NFL]] to suspend Williams.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news;_ylt=AkABrJWmr.lr9t5MmXUgyMlDubYF?slug=ap-starcaps-nflsuspensions]</ref>\n\nIn the 2009 season, Williams made 44 tackles, 2 sacks, and 2 forced fumbles. He announced that he might retire after the season, but decided to come back for one more year in 2010.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\">{{cite news |first=Chip |last=Scoggins |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Vikings Expect Williams to Return |url=http://www.startribune.com/sports/vikings/blogs/84634952.html |work=[[Star Tribune]] |publisher= |date=2010-02-17 |accessdate=2010-04-28 }}</ref> He was the oldest defensive player in the NFL.\n\nOn March 2, 2011, Williams announced that he would not re-sign with the Vikings for the 2011 season. \"Everything\u2019s good. I am not coming back. Going to go finish elsewhere.\" He ended his [[NFL]] career playing [[nose tackle]] when he retired.<ref>http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/03/03/pat-williams-no-longer-trusts-the-vikings/</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2013, Pat Williams signed a one-day contract so that he could retire as a Minnesota Viking.\n\nNow, Pat Williams coaches at Wossman High School as a defensive line coach.\n\n==NFL statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! Games !! Combined Tackles !! Tackles !! Assisted Tackles !! Sacks !! Forced Fumbles !! Fumble Recoveries !! Interceptions !! Touchdowns\n|-\n| [[1998 NFL season|1998]] || [[1998 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 13 || 12 || 11 || 1 || 3.5 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[1999 NFL season|1999]] || [[1999 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 32 || 25 || 7 || 2.5 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2000 NFL season|2000]] || [[2000 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 55 || 37 || 18 || 2.5 || 1 || 2 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2001 NFL season|2001]] || [[2001 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 13 || 59 || 41 || 18 || 1.5 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2002 NFL season|2002]] || [[2002 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 83 || 53 || 30 || 0.5 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2003 NFL season|2003]] || [[2003 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 81 || 54 || 27 || 0.0 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| [[2004 NFL season|2004]] || [[2004 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 53 || 37 || 16 || 2.5 || 0 || 1 || 1 || 1\n|-\n| [[2005 NFL season|2005]] || [[2005 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]] || 16 || 66 || 41 || 25 || 1.5 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2006 NFL season|2006]] || [[2006 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]] || 16 || 44 || 37 || 7 || 1.0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2007 NFL season|2007]] || [[2007 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]] || 16 || 62 || 43 || 19 || 2.0 || 0 || 2 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2008 NFL season|2008]] || [[2008 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]] || 14 || 44 || 31 || 13 || 1.0 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2009 NFL season|2009]] || [[2009 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]] || 15 || 44 || 34 || 10 || 2.0 || 2 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2010 NFL season|2010]] || [[2010 Minnesota Vikings season|MIN]] || 16 || 30 || 22 || 8 || 0.0 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| Career || [[Buffalo Bills|BUF]]/[[Minnesota Vikings|MIN]]|| 199 || 665 || 466 || 199 || 20.5 || 8 || 9 || 1 || 2\n|}<ref name=ESPN>{{cite web|title=Pat Williams Stats|url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/stats/_/id/1356/pat-williams|website=ESPN|publisher=ESPN Internet Ventures|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Footballstats |pfr=W/WillPa20}}\n*[http://www.vikings.com/team/roster/Pat-Williams/c7acea89-76de-4fda-98ae-2bd156bd8ce4 Minnesota Vikings bio]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Pat}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Monroe, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American football defensive tackles]]\n[[Category:Navarro Bulldogs football players]]\n[[Category:Texas A&M Aggies football players]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bills players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Vikings players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Northeastern Oklahoma A&M Golden Norsemen football players]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Patrick Williams|Patrick Williams}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Pat Williams\n|image=Pat Williams at 2009 Pro Bowl.jpg\n|image_size=150\n|caption=Pat Williams in the [[2009 Pro Bowl]].\n|number=94\n|position=[[Defensive tackle]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1972|10|24|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Monroe, Louisiana]]\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=3\n|weight_lbs=317\n|highlights=\n* 3\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2007 Pro Bowl|2006]]\u2013[[2009 Pro Bowl|2008]])\n* Second-team [[All-Pro]] ([[2007 All-Pro Team|2007]])\n|high_school=[[Wossman High School|Monroe (LA) Wossman]]\n|college=[[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]]\n|undraftedyear=1997\n|pastteams=\n* [[Buffalo Bills]] ({{NFL Year|1997}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2004}})\n* [[Minnesota Vikings]] ({{NFL Year|2005}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2010}})\n|statlabel1=[[Tackle (football move)|Tackle]]s\n|statvalue1=566\n|statlabel2=[[Quarterback sack|Sack]]s\n|statvalue2=20.5\n|statlabel3=[[Fumble|Forced fumbles]]\n|statvalue3=8\n|statlabel4=[[Fumble|Fumble recoveries]]\n|statvalue4=9\n|statlabel5=[[Interception]]s\n|statvalue5=1\n|statlabel6=[[Touchdown|Defensive touchdowns]]\n|statvalue6=2\n|nfl=WIL462033\n}}\n\n'''Patrick Williams Sr.''' (born October 24, 1972) is a former [[American football]] [[defensive tackle]] who played in the [[National Football League]] (NFL) for fourteen seasons.  He played [[college football]] for [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M University]].  He was signed by the [[Buffalo Bills]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] in 1997.  Williams also played for the [[Minnesota Vikings]], with whom he was a three-time [[Pro Bowl]] selection. Marneshia Williams daughter Montrel Williams son\n\n==College career==\nAfter graduating from [[Wossman High School]] in Monroe, Louisiana, Williams attended [[Navarro College]], where he was a two-time [[junior college]] All-American in 1992 and 1993. He initially transferred to [[Texas A&M University]] in 1994, but failed the math portion of a junior-college exit exam and was ruled ineligible for the [[1994 NCAA Division I-A football season|1994 season]]. He transferred again to [[Northeastern Oklahoma A&M College]], where he graduated in 1995, before returning to Texas A&M. Williams earned 2nd-team All-SWC as a junior in 1995 in only 6 starts. He also started 8 games and appeared in 11 as a senior.\n\n==Professional career==\n===Buffalo Bills===\nWilliams went undrafted in the [[1997 NFL Draft]], and signed with the [[Buffalo Bills]] as an [[undrafted free agent]] the same year. He played in just one game his rookie season. During the 1998\u20132000 seasons, he was a regular contributor, but did not become a regular starter until the 2001 season. In 2000, he was named to USA Today\u2019s All-Joe Team, recognizing the NFL\u2019s most \"overlooked, ignored and hard-working\" players.<ref name=\"Minnesota Vikings Bio\" /> Williams intercepted his first career pass and returned it 20 yards for a touchdown, picking off [[Miami Dolphins]] quarterback [[A. J. Feeley]] on December 5, 2004, sealing the win for Buffalo 42-32 and breaking open a 3-point game with 1:55 left to play.<ref name=\"Minnesota Vikings Bio\" /> Williams was named 2003 winner of the [[Ed Block Courage Award]] by his teammates.<ref name=\"Minnesota Vikings Bio\">[http://www.vikings.com/team/roster/Pat-Williams/c7acea89-76de-4fda-98ae-2bd156bd8ce4 Minnesota Vikings Bio]</ref> During his final four seasons with the Bills (2001\u20132004), he started in all but four games. He became a free agent after the 2004 season.\n\n===Minnesota Vikings===\nPrior to the 2005 season, Williams signed with the [[Minnesota Vikings]], the 1st signing for the team in 2005 free agency and a priority signing. Following an advice by then defensive coordinator [[Mike Tomlin]], Williams lost 15 pounds in the offseason. Williams played [[nose tackle]] in the [[Minnesota Vikings]] [[4-3 defense]], with teammate [[Kevin Williams (defensive tackle)|Kevin Williams]] playing the Under Tackle position. They were known collectively as the \"Williams Wall\" as well as the \"Williams Wrecking Crew\" due to their physical presence at the line of scrimmage, an attribute that helped them lead the Vikings to the best rushing defense in the league for three consecutive seasons (2006-2008). As a player for the Vikings, he was selected to his first [[Pro Bowl]] in 2006, and followed with consecutive selections in 2007 and 2008. He was also a second-team All-Pro selection in 2007.\n\nOn December 2, 2008, Pat and teammate [[Kevin Williams (defensive tackle)|Kevin Williams]] were suspended for 4 games by the league for violating its anti-doping policy, for use of a [[diuretic]], which can be used a [[masking agent]] for [[steroid]] use.<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=NFL Suspends Six Players for Doping Violations |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/football/nfl/12/02/nfl.ap/index.html |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |publisher= |date=2008-12-02 |accessdate= |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205093105/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/football/nfl/12/02/nfl.ap/index.html |archivedate=December 5, 2008 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80cfe423&template=without-video&confirm=true|title=NFL suspends six players for four games each}}</ref> It is believed that the diuretic was found in a weight-loss supplement that he had been taking.<ref name=\"SI\" /> Williams, along with Kevin Williams, appealed the suspension to a Minnesota federal court; the judge ruled against the NFL's decision and allowed all suspended players, including Williams, to play until a further review of the case.\n\nOn April 28, 2011, the [[Minnesota Supreme Court]] declined to consider Williams' appeal of the case, clearing the way for the [[NFL]] to suspend Williams.<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/news;_ylt=AkABrJWmr.lr9t5MmXUgyMlDubYF?slug=ap-starcaps-nflsuspensions]</ref>\n\nIn the 2009 season, Williams made 44 tackles, 2 sacks, and 2 forced fumbles. He announced that he might retire after the season, but decided to come back for one more year in 2010.<ref name=\"Star Tribune\">{{cite news |first=Chip |last=Scoggins |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Vikings Expect Williams to Return |url=http://www.startribune.com/sports/vikings/blogs/84634952.html |work=[[Star Tribune]] |publisher= |date=2010-02-17 |accessdate=2010-04-28 }}</ref> He was the oldest defensive player in the NFL.\n\nOn March 2, 2011, Williams announced that he would not re-sign with the Vikings for the 2011 season. \"Everything\u2019s good. I am not coming back. Going to go finish elsewhere.\" He ended his [[NFL]] career playing [[nose tackle]] when he retired.<ref>http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/03/03/pat-williams-no-longer-trusts-the-vikings/</ref>\n\nOn April 23, 2013, Pat Williams signed a one-day contract so that he could retire as a Minnesota Viking.\n\nNow, Pat Williams coaches at Wossman High School as a defensive line coach.\n\n==NFL statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Team !! Games !! Combined Tackles !! Tackles !! Assisted Tackles !! Sacks !! Forced Fumbles !! Fumble Recoveries !! Interceptions !! Touchdowns\n|-\n| [[1998 NFL season|1998]] || [[1998 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 13 || 12 || 11 || 1 || 3.5 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[1999 NFL season|1999]] || [[1999 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 32 || 25 || 7 || 2.5 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2000 NFL season|2000]] || [[2000 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 55 || 37 || 18 || 2.5 || 1 || 2 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2001 NFL season|2001]] || [[2001 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 13 || 59 || 41 || 18 || 1.5 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2002 NFL season|2002]] || [[2002 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 83 || 53 || 30 || 0.5 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| [[2003 NFL season|2003]] || [[2003 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 81 || 54 || 27 || 0.0 || 0 || 1 || 0 || 1\n|-\n| [[2004 NFL season|2004]] || [[2004 Buffalo Bills season|BUF]] || 16 || 53 || 37 || 16 || 2.5 ||