{"title_page": "Kim Daugaard", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Kim Daugaard\n| image =\n| fullname = Kim Daugaard Hansen\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1974|3|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Herf\u00f8lge]], Denmark\n| height = 1.80 m\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[HB K\u00f8ge]] (assistant)\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[HB K\u00f8ge|Herf\u00f8lge Boldklub]] \n| youthyears2 =\n| youthclubs2 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]\n| years1 = 1993\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]\n| caps1 = 336 \n| goals1 = 34\n| years2 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs2 = Frederiksv\u00e6rk FK\n| caps2 = 1 \n| goals2 = 0\n| totalcaps = 337\n| totalgoals = 34\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\u20131993\n| nationalteam1 = Denmark U19\n| nationalcaps1 = 2\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1994\u20131996\n| nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U21]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 17\n| nationalgoals2 = 1\n| manageryears1 = 2009\u20132011\n| managerclubs1 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2 = 2012\u20132013\n| managerclubs2 = Frederiksv\u00e6rk FK (player-assistant)\n| manageryears3 = 2014\u20132016\n| managerclubs3 = [[HB K\u00f8ge]] U19 (assistant)\n| manageryears4 = 2014\u2013\n| managerclubs4 = [[HB K\u00f8ge]] (assistant)\n}}\n'''Kim Daugaard Hansen''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8d\u0251wk\u0252\u02c0}}; born 29 March 1974) is a Danish [[Association football|football]] coach and former professional player, who currently works as assistant coach [[HB K\u00f8ge]].\n\nHe played as a [[midfielder]] for [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] for his entire career.<ref name=\"df\">[http://www.danskfodbold.com/spiller.php?spillerid=10133&ligaid=2001 Kim Daugaard Hansen] at DanskFodbold.com</ref> He played more than 450 games for the club, and won five [[Danish Superliga]] championships and five [[Danish Cup]] titles, and was named 1998 [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] ''Player of the Year''. Daugaard played 17 games and scored one goal for the [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Danish under-21 national team]] from 1994 to 1996.\n\n==Playing career==\nDaugaard played at youth level for [[Herf\u00f8lge BK]] before moving to Br\u00f8ndby IF,<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\">{{in lang|da}} [http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=11&id=33 Br\u00f8ndby IF profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128145838/http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=11&id=33 |date=28 November 2006 }}</ref> for whom he represented the Danish under-19 national team.<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/> He signed his first professional contract with Br\u00f8ndby IF in January 1993, alongside under-19 national teammates [[Allan Ravn]] and [[Ole Puggaard]]. He made his senior debut for Br\u00f8ndby on 3 July 1993,<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\"/> and made his [[Danish Superliga]] debut in April 1994.<ref name=\"df\"/> Daugaard was a part of the Br\u00f8ndby team which won the 1994 [[Danish Cup]]. He was called up for the Danish under-21 national team in May 1994, and he went on to play 17 matches and score a single goal until July 1996.<ref name=\"dbuofficial\">[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/4769&allmatch=1#match Kim Daugaard \u2013 Alle hold (Alle kampe)] at [[Danish Football Association]]</ref>\n\nHe established himself in the Br\u00f8ndby starting line-up during the [[1995\u201396 Danish Superliga|1995\u201396 Superliga]] season, under manager [[Ebbe Skovdahl]]. Daugaard only missed eight of 99 league games as Br\u00f8ndby won three [[Danish Superliga]] championships in a row,<ref name=\"df\"/> from 1996 to 1998, as well as the 1998 Danish Cup, and he won the 1998 Br\u00f8ndby IF ''Player of the Year'' award.<ref name=\"playeroftheyear\">[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33492 \u00c5rets Spiller] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709091818/http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33492 |date=9 July 2010 }} at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref> He was called up for the Danish national league team, comprising the best players of the Danish Superliga, on a number of occasions, and played seven unofficial national league team games, scoring one goal, from January 1997 to February 2000.<ref>[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/4769&teamtypeid=2165&off=0#match Kim Daugaard \u2013 Ligalandshold (Alle uofficielle kampe)] at [[Danish Football Association]]</ref>\n\nWhen [[\u00c5ge Hareide]] was appointed new Br\u00f8ndby manager in January 2000, and for the [[2000\u201301 Danish Superliga|2000\u201301 Superliga]] season, Daugaard received stiff competition from Swedish players [[Krister Nordin]] and [[Magnus Svensson (footballer)|Magnus Svensson]]. Daugaard eventually reclaimed his starting position in the [[Danish Superliga 2003-04|2003\u201304 Superliga]] season, under new coach [[Michael Laudrup]]. He played 31 of 33 games in the [[Danish Superliga 2004-05|2004\u201305 Superliga]] season,<ref name=\"df\"/> as Br\u00f8ndby won the 2005 Superliga championship. With a goal in the 2005 [[Danish Cup]] final, he helped Br\u00f8ndby win [[Double (association football)|the Double]] that year. Daugaard helped Br\u00f8ndby win the 2008 Danish Cup, before ending his career in the winter 2008.<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\"/> Daugaard played a total 466 games for Br\u00f8ndby in all competitions,<ref>[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=32438 1. holdsspillere i Br\u00f8ndby IF] at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref> including 336 games and 34 goals in the Superliga.<ref name=\"df\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\nBetween January 2009 og 1 September 2011, Daugaard worked as assistant coach for [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]].<ref>[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=49288&id=145 Kim Daugaard assistenttr\u00e6ner pr. 1/1-09] at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref> In July 2012, he became part of the coaching staff at Frederiksv\u00e6rk FK and officially became a playing assistant coach later that year.<ref>[http://dinby.dk/frederiksvaerk-ugeblad/jeg-vil-rykke-noget - Jeg vil rykke noget], Ugeblad Frederiksv\u00e6rk og Halsn\u00e6s Posten</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* '''[[Danish Superliga]]''' (5 titles)\n**[[1995\u201396 Danish Superliga|1995\u201396]], [[1996\u201397 Danish Superliga|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Danish Superliga|1997\u201398]], [[2001\u201302 Danish Superliga|2001\u201302]], [[2004\u201305 Danish Superliga|2004\u201305]]\n*'''[[Danish Cup]]''' (5 titles)\n**1993\u201394, 1997\u201398, 2002\u201303, 2004\u201305, 2007\u201308\n*'''1998 [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] ''Player of the Year'''''\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/4769 Danish national team profile]\n*{{in lang|da}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20061128145838/http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=11&id=33 Br\u00f8ndby IF profile]\n\n{{Br\u00f8ndby IF Player of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daugaard, Kim}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from K\u00f8ge Municipality]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Danish footballers]]\n[[Category:Denmark under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Br\u00f8ndby IF players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football biography\n| name= Kim Daugaard\n| image =\n| fullname = Kim Daugaard Hansen\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1974|3|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Herf\u00f8lge]], Denmark\n| height = 1.80 m\n| position = [[Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = [[HB K\u00f8ge]] (assistant)\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthyears2 =\n| youthclubs1 = [[HB K\u00f8ge|Herf\u00f8lge Boldklub]] \n| youthclubs2 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]\n| years1 = 1993\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]]\n| caps1 = 336 \n| goals1 = 34\n| years2 = 2012\u20132013\n| clubs2 = Frederiksv\u00e6rk FK\n| caps2 = 1 \n| goals2 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 1992\u20131993 \n| nationalyears2 = 1994\u20131996\n| nationalteam1 = Denmark U19 \n| nationalteam2 = [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Denmark U21]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 2 \n| nationalgoals1 = 0 \n| nationalcaps2 = 17 \n| nationalgoals2 = 1\n| manageryears1= 2009\u20132011\n| managerclubs1= [[Br\u00f8ndby IF|Br\u00f8ndby]] (assistant)\n| manageryears2= 2012\u20132013\n| managerclubs2= Frederiksv\u00e6rk FK (player-assistant)\n| manageryears3= 2014\u20132016\n| managerclubs3= [[HB K\u00f8ge]] U19 (assistant)\n| manageryears4= 2014\u2013\n| managerclubs4= [[HB K\u00f8ge]] (assistant)\n}}\n'''Kim Daugaard Hansen''' ({{IPA-da|\u02c8d\u0251wk\u0252\u02c0}}; born 29 March 1974) is a Danish [[Association football|football]] coach and former professional player, who currently works as assistant coach [[HB K\u00f8ge]].\n\nHe played as a [[midfielder]] for [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] for his entire career.<ref name=\"df\">[http://www.danskfodbold.com/spiller.php?spillerid=10133&ligaid=2001 Kim Daugaard Hansen] at DanskFodbold.com</ref> He played more than 450 games for the club, and won five [[Danish Superliga]] championships and five [[Danish Cup]] titles, and was named 1998 [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] ''Player of the Year''. Daugaard played 17 games and scored one goal for the [[Denmark national under-21 football team|Danish under-21 national team]] from 1994 to 1996.\n\n==Playing career==\nDaugaard played at youth level for [[Herf\u00f8lge BK]] before moving to Br\u00f8ndby IF,<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\">{{in lang|da}} [http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=11&id=33 Br\u00f8ndby IF profile] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128145838/http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=11&id=33 |date=28 November 2006 }}</ref> for whom he represented the Danish under-19 national team.<ref name=\"dbuofficial\"/> He signed his first professional contract with Br\u00f8ndby IF in January 1993, alongside under-19 national teammates [[Allan Ravn]] and [[Ole Puggaard]]. He made his senior debut for Br\u00f8ndby on 3 July 1993,<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\"/> and made his [[Danish Superliga]] debut in April 1994.<ref name=\"df\"/> Daugaard was a part of the Br\u00f8ndby team which won the 1994 [[Danish Cup]]. He was called up for the Danish under-21 national team in May 1994, and he went on to play 17 matches and score a single goal until July 1996.<ref name=\"dbuofficial\">[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/4769&allmatch=1#match Kim Daugaard \u2013 Alle hold (Alle kampe)] at [[Danish Football Association]]</ref>\n\nHe established himself in the Br\u00f8ndby starting line-up during the [[Danish Superliga 1995-96|1995\u201396 Superliga]] season, under manager [[Ebbe Skovdahl]]. Daugaard only missed eight of 99 league games as Br\u00f8ndby won three [[Danish Superliga]] championships in a row,<ref name=\"df\"/> from 1996 to 1998, as well as the 1998 Danish Cup, and he won the 1998 Br\u00f8ndby IF ''Player of the Year'' award.<ref name=\"playeroftheyear\">[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33492 \u00c5rets Spiller] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100709091818/http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=33492 |date=9 July 2010 }} at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref> He was called up for the Danish national league team, comprising the best players of the Danish Superliga, on a number of occasions, and played seven unofficial national league team games, scoring one goal, from January 1997 to February 2000.<ref>[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/4769&teamtypeid=2165&off=0#match Kim Daugaard \u2013 Ligalandshold (Alle uofficielle kampe)] at [[Danish Football Association]]</ref>\n\nWhen [[\u00c5ge Hareide]] was appointed new Br\u00f8ndby manager in January 2000, and for the [[Danish Superliga 2000-01|2000\u201301 Superliga]] season, Daugaard received stiff competition from [[Sweden|Swedish]] players [[Krister Nordin]] and [[Magnus Svensson (footballer)|Magnus Svensson]]. Daugaard eventually reclaimed his starting position in the [[Danish Superliga 2003-04|2003\u201304 Superliga]] season, under new coach [[Michael Laudrup]]. He played 31 of 33 games in the [[Danish Superliga 2004-05|2004\u201305 Superliga]] season,<ref name=\"df\"/> as Br\u00f8ndby won the 2005 Superliga championship. With a goal in the 2005 [[Danish Cup]] final, he helped Br\u00f8ndby win [[Double (association football)|the Double]] that year. Daugaard helped Br\u00f8ndby win the 2008 Danish Cup, before ending his career in the winter 2008.<ref name=\"br\u00f8ndby\"/> Daugaard played a total 466 games for Br\u00f8ndby in all competitions,<ref>[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=32438 1. holdsspillere i Br\u00f8ndby IF] at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref> including 336 games and 34 goals in the Superliga.<ref name=\"df\"/>\n\n==Coaching career==\nBetween January 2009 og 1 September 2011, Daugaard worked as Assistant Coach for [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]].<ref>[http://brondby.com/article.asp?aid=49288&id=145 Kim Daugaard assistenttr\u00e6ner pr. 1/1-09] at [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]]</ref> In July 2012, he became part of the coaching staff at Frederiksv\u00e6rk FK and officially became a playing assistant coach later that year.<ref>[http://dinby.dk/frederiksvaerk-ugeblad/jeg-vil-rykke-noget - Jeg vil rykke noget], Ugeblad Frederiksv\u00e6rk og Halsn\u00e6s Posten</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n* '''[[Danish Superliga]]''' (5 titles)\n**[[Danish Superliga 1995-96|1995\u201396]], [[Danish Superliga 1996-97|1996\u201397]], [[Danish Superliga 1997-98|1997\u201398]], [[Danish Superliga 2001-02|2001\u201302]], [[Danish Superliga 2004-05|2004\u201305]]\n*'''[[Danish Cup]]''' (5 titles)\n**1993\u201394, 1997\u201398, 2002\u201303, 2004\u201305, 2007\u201308\n*'''1998 [[Br\u00f8ndby IF]] ''Player of the Year'''''\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.dbu.dk/landshold/landsholdsdatabasen/PlayerInfo/4769 Danish national team profile]\n*{{in lang|da}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20061128145838/http://www.brondby.com/player.asp?sid=11&id=33 Br\u00f8ndby IF profile]\n\n{{Br\u00f8ndby IF Player of the Year}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Daugaard, Kim}}