{"title_page": "Patrick Williams (Louisiana politician)", "text_new": "{{short description|American politician}}\n{{other people|Patrick Williams|Patrick Williams}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name= Patrick Charles Williams\n|state_house=Louisiana\n|district=4th\n|term_start=April 2007\n|term_end=January 2016\n|preceded=[[Cedric Glover]]\n|succeeded=Cedric Glover\n|birth_date={{birth year and age|1963|11}}\n|birth_place=\n|residence=[[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|resting_place=\n|spouse=\n|children= \n|parents=\n|relations=\n|party= [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|occupation=[[Business]]man \n|religion=\n|alma_mater={{unbulleted list|[[Southern University]]|[[Centenary College of Louisiana]]|[[Waldon University]]}}\n|footnotes=\n}}\n'''Patrick Charles Williams''' (born November 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://voterportal.sos.la.gov/Home/Home?uid=621811|title=Patrick Williams, November 1963|publisher=[[Louisiana Secretary of State]]|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> is a small [[business]]man from [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]], who is an [[African-American]] [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[Louisiana State Legislature|Louisiana House of Representatives]] for District 4 in [[Caddo Parish, Louisiana|Caddo Parish]] in the northwestern corner of his state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://house.louisiana.gov/H_PDFdocs/HouseMembers1812_2008.pdf |title=Membership of the Louisiana House of Representatives, 1812-2012 |publisher=house.louisiana.gov |accessdate=April 23, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331104823/http://house.louisiana.gov/H_PDFdocs/HouseMembers1812_2008.pdf |archivedate=March 31, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nWilliams received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Architecture]] from the [[historically black]] [[Southern University]] in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]] and a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree from the [[United Methodist Church|United Methodist]]-affiliated [[Centenary College of Louisiana|Centenary College]] of Shreveport.<ref name=pcw>{{cite web|url=http://house.louisiana.gov/H_Reps/members.asp?ID=4|title=Patrick Williams|publisher=house.louisiana.gov|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams received d doctoral degree in Applied Management & Decision Science Technology from [[Walden University]] in 2015.\n\nWilliams has also resided in  [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]; [[Swainsboro, Georgia|Swainsboro]], and [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], dates unavailable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intelius.com/results.php?ReportType=1&formname=name&qf=patrick&qmi=c&qn=williams&qcs=shreveport%2C+la.&focusfirst=1|title=Patrick Charles Williams|publisher=intelius.com|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Political life==\nIn 2003, Williams ran unsuccessfully for the state House against fellow Democrat [[Cedric Glover]], who had been first elected in 1995. Glover prevailed in the [[nonpartisan blanket primary]] with 5,902 votes (62.3 percent) to Williams's 3,567 (37.7 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/10042003/10042003_Legislative.html|title=Election Results|date=October 4, 2003|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> After Glover was elected [[List of mayors of Shreveport, Louisiana|mayor of Shreveport]], Williams won the right to succeed him in the [[special election]] low-turnout [[runoff election|runoff]] held on March 31, 2007. In this race, Williams, with 2,321 votes (65.7 percent) defeated fellow Democrat Larry Ferdinand, who polled 1,214 votes (34.3 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/03312007/03312007_Legislative.html|title=Election Results|date=March 31, 2007|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\nSeven months later, Williams won his first full term in the state House when he defeated still another Democrat, Billy Wayne, 7,009 (75.2 percent) to 2,311 (24.8 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/10202007/10202007_Legislative.html|title=Election Results|date=October 20, 2007|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> Williams was unopposed for his second full term in the 2011 primary election.\n\nIn 2014, Williams sought to succeed his former intra-party rival, Cedric Glover, who was [[Term limit|term-limited]] as mayor of Shreveport. In the November 4 primary for mayor, Williams finished in third place with 12,880 votes (21.7 percent). Eventual winner [[Ollie Tyler]], a retired African-American educator, led with 26,017 votes (43.7 percent). In second place was an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]] candidate, [[Lawyer|attorney]], Victoria Provenza (born 1960), with 15,155 votes (25.5 percent). Provenza hence edged Williams out of a runoff berth by 2,275 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/11042014/11042014_09.html|title=Election Results|date=November 4, 2014|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams is a member of the Louisiana Black Caucus, the Rural Caucus, and the Democratic Caucus.\nHe is vice-chair of the House Ways and Means Committee and serves as well on Health and Welfare, the\nHouse Executive Committee, and the Joint Legislative Committee on Capital Outlay.<ref name=pcw/>\n\nIn 2014, Representative Williams was rated 44 to 62 percent by the [[Louisiana Association of Business and Industry]] and 25 to 50 percent by the [[National Federation of Independent Business]]. He scored 50 percent from the [[Conservative (politics)|conservative]] [[Louisiana Family Forum]] but 100 percent from [[Right to Life]]. He supported the requirement that [[abortion]] providers maintain hospital admitting privileges near their clinics. He received a 75 percent rating from the Louisiana Association of Educators. He voted to [[repeal]] anti-sodomy laws, but the measure failed to pass the entire House.<ref name=votingrecords>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/35371/patrick-williams#.VTkUgMstEqQ|title=Patrick C. Williams' Political Summary|publisher=[[Project Vote Smart]]|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Williams voted to reduce penalties for possession of [[marijuana]]. He voted to repeal mandatory retirement for judges. He opposed lifetime [[concealed carry]] gun permits and voted to make information on the permits a matter of public record. In 2012, he opposed the measure to require drug testing for welfare recipients. He supported the ban on use of telephones while driving.<ref name=votingrecords/>\n\nWilliams did not seek reelection to a third full term in the House in the upcoming primary election scheduled for October 24, 2015. Three black Democrats, Reginald Johnson, Fred Moss, IV, and former Mayor Cedric Glover, ran to succeed Williams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://710keel.com/candidates-qualified-in-statewide-elections/|title=Candidates Qualified in Statewide Elections|publisher=[[KEEL (AM)]]|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> Glover emerged victorious to return to the former House seat.\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|United States|Los Angeles|Virginia|Georgia (U.S. state)|Politics}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n \n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box \n|before=[[Cedric Glover]]\n|title=[[Louisiana State Legislature|Louisiana State Representative for<br /> District 4 (Caddo Parish)]]\nPatrick Charles Williams\n|years=2007&ndash;\n|after=[[Cedric Glover]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Patrick C.}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Members of the Louisiana House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Southern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Centenary College of Louisiana alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cheyenne, Wyoming]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American politiciain}}\n{{other people|Patrick Williams|Patrick Williams}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name= Patrick Charles Williams\n|state_house=Louisiana\n|district=4th\n|term_start=April 2007\n|term_end=January 2016\n|preceded=[[Cedric Glover]]\n|succeeded=Cedric Glover\n|birth_date={{birth year and age|1963|11}}\n|birth_place=\n|residence=[[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|resting_place=\n|spouse=\n|children= \n|parents=\n|relations=\n|party= [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|occupation=[[Business]]man \n|religion=\n|alma_mater={{unbulleted list|[[Southern University]]|[[Centenary College of Louisiana]]|[[Waldon University]]}}\n|footnotes=\n}}\n'''Patrick Charles Williams''' (born November 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://voterportal.sos.la.gov/Home/Home?uid=621811|title=Patrick Williams, November 1963|publisher=[[Louisiana Secretary of State]]|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> is a small [[business]]man from [[Shreveport, Louisiana|Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]], who is an [[African-American]] [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] member of the [[Louisiana State Legislature|Louisiana House of Representatives]] for District 4 in [[Caddo Parish, Louisiana|Caddo Parish]] in the northwestern corner of his state.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://house.louisiana.gov/H_PDFdocs/HouseMembers1812_2008.pdf |title=Membership of the Louisiana House of Representatives, 1812-2012 |publisher=house.louisiana.gov |accessdate=April 23, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100331104823/http://house.louisiana.gov/H_PDFdocs/HouseMembers1812_2008.pdf |archivedate=March 31, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nWilliams received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree in [[Architecture]] from the [[historically black]] [[Southern University]] in [[Baton Rouge, Louisiana|Baton Rouge]] and a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree from the [[United Methodist Church|United Methodist]]-affiliated [[Centenary College of Louisiana|Centenary College]] of Shreveport.<ref name=pcw>{{cite web|url=http://house.louisiana.gov/H_Reps/members.asp?ID=4|title=Patrick Williams|publisher=house.louisiana.gov|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams received d doctoral degree in Applied Management & Decision Science Technology from [[Walden University]] in 2015.\n\nWilliams has also resided in  [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]]; [[Swainsboro, Georgia|Swainsboro]], and [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], dates unavailable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intelius.com/results.php?ReportType=1&formname=name&qf=patrick&qmi=c&qn=williams&qcs=shreveport%2C+la.&focusfirst=1|title=Patrick Charles Williams|publisher=intelius.com|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Political life==\nIn 2003, Williams ran unsuccessfully for the state House against fellow Democrat [[Cedric Glover]], who had been first elected in 1995. Glover prevailed in the [[nonpartisan blanket primary]] with 5,902 votes (62.3 percent) to Williams's 3,567 (37.7 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/10042003/10042003_Legislative.html|title=Election Results|date=October 4, 2003|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> After Glover was elected [[List of mayors of Shreveport, Louisiana|mayor of Shreveport]], Williams won the right to succeed him in the [[special election]] low-turnout [[runoff election|runoff]] held on March 31, 2007. In this race, Williams, with 2,321 votes (65.7 percent) defeated fellow Democrat Larry Ferdinand, who polled 1,214 votes (34.3 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/03312007/03312007_Legislative.html|title=Election Results|date=March 31, 2007|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\nSeven months later, Williams won his first full term in the state House when he defeated still another Democrat, Billy Wayne, 7,009 (75.2 percent) to 2,311 (24.8 percent).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/10202007/10202007_Legislative.html|title=Election Results|date=October 20, 2007|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref> Williams was unopposed for his second full term in the 2011 primary election.\n\nIn 2014, Williams sought to succeed his former intra-party rival, Cedric Glover, who was [[Term limit|term-limited]] as mayor of Shreveport. In the November 4 primary for mayor, Williams finished in third place with 12,880 votes (21.7 percent). Eventual winner [[Ollie Tyler]], a retired African-American educator, led with 26,017 votes (43.7 percent). In second place was an [[Independent (politics)|Independent]] candidate, [[Lawyer|attorney]], Victoria Provenza (born 1960), with 15,155 votes (25.5 percent). Provenza hence edged Williams out of a runoff berth by 2,275 votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://staticresults.sos.la.gov/11042014/11042014_09.html|title=Election Results|date=November 4, 2014|publisher=Louisiana Secretary of State|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWilliams is a member of the Louisiana Black Caucus, the Rural Caucus, and the Democratic Caucus.\nHe is vice-chair of the House Ways and Means Committee and serves as well on Health and Welfare, the\nHouse Executive Committee, and the Joint Legislative Committee on Capital Outlay.<ref name=pcw/>\n\nIn 2014, Representative Williams was rated 44 to 62 percent by the [[Louisiana Association of Business and Industry]] and 25 to 50 percent by the [[National Federation of Independent Business]]. He scored 50 percent from the [[Conservative (politics)|conservative]] [[Louisiana Family Forum]] but 100 percent from [[Right to Life]]. He supported the requirement that [[abortion]] providers maintain hospital admitting privileges near their clinics. He received a 75 percent rating from the Louisiana Association of Educators. He voted to [[repeal]] anti-sodomy laws, but the measure failed to pass the entire House.<ref name=votingrecords>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/35371/patrick-williams#.VTkUgMstEqQ|title=Patrick C. Williams' Political Summary|publisher=[[Project Vote Smart]]|accessdate=April 23, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Williams voted to reduce penalties for possession of [[marijuana]]. He voted to repeal mandatory retirement for judges. He opposed lifetime [[concealed carry]] gun permits and voted to make information on the permits a matter of public record. In 2012, he opposed the measure to require drug testing for welfare recipients. He supported the ban on use of telephones while driving.<ref name=votingrecords/>\n\nWilliams did not seek reelection to a third full term in the House in the upcoming primary election scheduled for October 24, 2015. Three black Democrats, Reginald Johnson, Fred Moss, IV, and former Mayor Cedric Glover, ran to succeed Williams.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://710keel.com/candidates-qualified-in-statewide-elections/|title=Candidates Qualified in Statewide Elections|publisher=[[KEEL (AM)]]|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref> Glover emerged victorious to return to the former House seat.\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography|United States|Los Angeles|Virginia|Georgia (U.S. state)|Politics}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n \n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box \n|before=[[Cedric Glover]]\n|title=[[Louisiana State Legislature|Louisiana State Representative for<br /> District 4 (Caddo Parish)]]\nPatrick Charles Williams\n|years=2007&ndash;\n|after=[[Cedric Glover]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Williams, Patrick C.}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Members of the Louisiana House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Democrats]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Shreveport, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:African-American state legislators in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Southern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Centenary College of Louisiana alumni]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Richmond, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cheyenne, Wyoming]]\n", "name_user": "DemonDays64", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changingshort descriptionfrom \"American politiciain\" to \"American politician\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Williams_(Louisiana_politician)"}
